NAME
    cut - remove sections from each line of files

SYNOPSIS
    cut OPTION... [FILE]...

DESCRIPTION
    Print selected parts of lines from each FILE to standard output.
    With no FILE, or when FILE is '-', read standard input.

    Exactly one of -b, -c, or -f must be specified.

OPTIONS
    -b LIST, --bytes=LIST
        Select only the bytes at positions given in LIST.

    -c LIST, --characters=LIST
        Select only the characters at positions in LIST.

    -d DELIM, --delimiter=DELIM
        Use DELIM as the field delimiter instead of TAB (used with -f).

    -f LIST, --fields=LIST
        Select only the fields given in LIST. Lines that do not contain
        the delimiter are printed unchanged unless -s is also given.

    -s, --only-delimited
        With -f, do not print lines that do not contain the delimiter.

    --complement
        Complement the selection; print bytes/chars/fields NOT in LIST.

    --output-delimiter=STRING
        Use STRING as the output delimiter. Default is the input
        delimiter (with -f) or no separator (with -bc).

    -z, --zero-terminated
        Line delimiter is NUL, not newline.

    --version
        Output version information and exit.

    --help
        Display help and exit.

LIST FORMAT
    LIST is a comma-separated sequence of ranges. A range is:
        N       Nth byte/character/field (1-based)
        N-M     From Nth to Mth
        N-      From Nth to end of line
        -M      From first to Mth

EXAMPLES
    cut -d: -f1 /etc/passwd
        Extract usernames (first colon-delimited field).

    cut -d, -f1,3 data.csv
        Extract columns 1 and 3 from CSV.

    cut -c1-10 file.txt
        Extract first 10 characters of each line.

    cut -d' ' -f2- sentence.txt
        Print all words after the first.

    cut --complement -d, -f2 data.csv
        Print all CSV columns except column 2.

EXIT STATUS
    0   Success.
    1   Error occurred.
